<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Cleared of Plotting Coup Charges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402213394 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
2000 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages contained within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Text] Joao da Costa has been cleared of charges [of 
plotting an attempted coup]. The opposition candidate to 
Guinea-Bissau's presidential elections has just been cleared of 
charges at Guinea-Bissau's Supreme Military Court. After the 
verdict was pronounced the first thing Joao da Costa did was to 
talk to us: 
  [Da Costa] "There were 14 defendants on trial at the Supreme 
Military Court and only three of them were cleared of charges: 
Joao da Costa, Tarmo (Anawai), and Gil (Sanha)." 
  [Announcer] That was a relieved Joao da Costa. 
  [Da Costa] "Thank God. I have just witnessed one of the 
greatest injustices ever." 
  [Announcer] That was Joao da Costa talking to Luis Ferreira. 
The leader of Guinea-Bissau's PRD [Democratic Renewal Party] has 
no doubt that had there not been international pressure his 
conviction would have been certain: 
  [Da Costa] "That is the regime. Had it been anyone else but 
Joao da Costa, I am sure they would have also been convicted. 
It is all because I am Joao da Costa, one of the opposition 
leaders, and international pressure helped me in being cleared." 

</TEXT>

